Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," added Cockell.
This discovery was not random.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA astrobiological Institute, which led the study, chose the Mono Lake due to the high arsenic content.
Since Arsen and phosphorus were chemically similar, she assumed that microbes who are both exposed may replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mostly based on the fact that it is chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for the organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
"But the difference is so big that Arsen works differently than phosphorus. It comes into our biochemical system, where it almost smashs everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exhibited the Bacterium GFAJ-1 of an rising arse concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can survive in arsens, it shows that an arsen-based life form can naturally occur, either on earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsen is more frequent.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsens is not new, but there has not yet been a working example.
Arsen was more frequent in the early years of earth, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
